{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Periplasmic Binding Protein (PBP)-dependent ATP-Binding Cassette (ABC) transporters are involved in the uptake of siderophores, heme, vitamin B12, or the divalent cations Mg2+ and Zn2+. PBP-dependent ABC transporters consist of a PBP, two transmembrane regions (TMs), and two cytoplasmic ABCs, and are mainly involved in importing solutes from the environment [[cite:PUB00080123]]. The solute is captured by the PBP which delivers it to a gated translocation pathway formed by the two TMs. The TMs are bundles of Î± helices that transverse the cytoplasmic membrane multiple times. The two ABCs bind and hydrolyze ATP and drive the transport reaction. Each TM has a prominent cytoplasmic loop which contacts an ABC and represents a conserved motif. The two TMs form either a homodimer (e.g. in the case of the BtuC subunits of the Escherichia coli BtuCD vitamin B12 transporter) [[cite:PUB00026953], [cite:PUB00049009]], a heterodimer (e.g. the TroC and TroD subunits of the Treponema pallidum general transition metal transporter, TroBCD) [[cite:PUB00078715], [cite:PUB00080135]], or a pseudo-heterodimer (e.g. the FhuB protein of the E. coli ferrichrome transporter, FhuBC) [[cite:PUB00080128], [cite:PUB00080129]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false} {"text" "<p>This subfamily consists of integral membrane components from a number of bacterial transport systems that have similar sequences [[cite:PUB00070765]], and include TroC and TroD, and ScaB (required for Mn2+ import in Streptococcus [[cite:PUB00088718]]).</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR037294", "name" "ABC transporter, BtuC-like", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"panther" {"PTHR30477" "ABC-TRANSPORTER METAL-BINDING PROTEIN"}, "pfam" {"PF00950" "ABC 3 transport family"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "ABC transporter, TroCD-like", "shor